{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511836"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:46:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:46:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11791"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11791","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11791"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.11,0.01,0.75,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4405"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79087"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4405"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11791"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64439"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11198"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6243"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6247"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26951"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42665"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43273"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44788"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79087"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner (GP) with a rash on her face and hands that has developed over the last month. The GP also notes that she has recently been diagnosed with breast cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn observation, the patient has a heliotrope rash with swelling around the eyes. It is also noted that there is a scaly patch in the scalp. There are papules on the backs of the patient\u0027s hands and she has ragged cuticles. The patient is instructed to stand up from her chair without using her arms. She struggles to do so and mentions that she has been a lot weaker than usual.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Psoriasis","Systemic Lupus Erythematosus","Lichen Planus","Dermatomyositis","Polymyositis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDermatomyositis\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. Many details in the history and examination suggest a diagnosis of dermatomyositis. The patient has a malignancy, has a characteristic lilac skin discolouration around the eyes (heliotrope rash), has papules on the hands (Gottron papules), has ragged cuticles and is presenting with muscle weakness. A skin biopsy and blood tests may be used to confirm the diagnosis. Though not present in this stem, other signs you may see in someone with dermatomyositis are fixed redness affecting the upper back and shoulders (shawl sign), photosensitivity, hyperkeratotic changes in the hand (mechanic\u0027s hands), Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon and calcinosis cutis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolymyositis\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While this may explain the muscle weakness, it fails to account for the skin changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic Lupus Erythematosus\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. This would likely be a key differential, however the constellation of symptoms is highly suggestive of dermatomyositis. In SLE, you may expect to find a malar rash, mouth ulcers or evidence of end organ pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsoriasis\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. This often presents as a scaly rash on the scalp, however this is the only part of the history that may point to psoriasis. Psoriasis does not explain the eye signs nor proximal myopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELichen Planus\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. This condition typically presents with purple, polygonal, pruritic papules, often on the wrists and ankles, and does not explain the muscle weakness or heliotrope rash.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Dermatomyositis often presents with a combination of skin changes and muscle weakness.","Dermatomyositis is associated with an increased risk of malignancy, particularly in adults.","Characteristic skin findings in dermatomyositis include heliotrope rash and Gottron\u0027s papules."],"references":["Waldman R, DeWane ME, Lu J. Dermatomyositis: Diagnosis and treatment. J Am Acad Dermatol. 2020 Feb;82(2):283-296. doi: 10.1016/j.jaad.2019.05.105. Epub 2019 Jul 4. PMID: 31279813. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31279813/","Cassard L, Seraly N, Riegert M, Patel A, Fernandez AP. Dermatomyositis: Practical Guidance and Unmet Needs. Immunotargets Ther. 2024 Mar 6;13:151-172. doi: 10.2147/ITT.S381472. PMID: 38464459; PMCID: PMC10924937. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10924937/","Marvi U, Chung L, Fiorentino DF. Clinical presentation and evaluation of dermatomyositis. Indian J Dermatol. 2012 Sep;57(5):375-81. doi: 10.4103/0019-5154.100486. PMID: 23112358; PMCID: PMC3482801. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3482801/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64439"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11791"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64439"},"attr